  <section class="category-info-block">
    <div class="container">
      <h2>PCB Cleaning Machines &amp; Industrial Cleaners</h2>
      <p>
        A PCB cleaning machine removes surface contamination from circuit boards before critical process steps. Dust, particles, fibers, and static-bonded debris cause defects throughout production. These contaminants lead to poor solder paste adhesion during screen printing, component misalignment during pick-and-place, and false failures during optical inspection. A well-specified circuit board cleaning machine removes defects at the source, improving yield and reducing rework costs long term.
      </p>

      <h3>Types of Industrial Cleaning Machines</h3>
      <p>
        DGSDK manufactures industrial cleaning machines for specific substrate types and production environments. Small to medium production lines and high-volume automated lines use different cleaning methods. The right machine depends on your substrate, line speed, and contamination profile:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>PCB Cleaning Machines</strong> — Adhesive roller-based circuit board cleaners that remove surface particles from both sides of PCBs without chemicals or water. These are the most common cleaning methods for SMT pre-print and pre-placement positions.</li>
        <li><strong>SMT Inline Cleaning Machines</strong> — Fully automatic inline machines with PLC control, matching conveyor speeds in continuous SMT production. The SMT600 Series uses dual upper and lower rollers with integrated static elimination.</li>
        <li><strong>FPC Cleaning Machines</strong> — Multi-axis precision cleaning systems for flexible printed circuits. Available in 4-axis and 8-axis configurations for different throughput requirements.</li>
        <li><strong>Optical Film Cleaning Machines</strong> — Large-format cleaning systems for optical films, polarizer sheets, and display substrates. Handles wide film widths without deformation or surface marking.</li>
        <li><strong>LCM Module Cleaning Machines</strong> — Industrial cleaning for liquid crystal modules before bonding, inspection, and packaging. Removes particles that cause optical defects in finished display units.</li>
        <li><strong>Backlight Panel Cleaning Machines</strong> — Precision cleaning for backlight units before assembly. Removes dust that causes bright spots and non-uniformity in finished panels.</li>
        <li><strong>CCL Cleaning Machines</strong> — Surface preparation cleaning for copper clad laminate boards before PCB manufacturing processes.</li>
        <li><strong>Inspection Stage Cleaning Machines</strong> — Positioned immediately before automated optical inspection (AOI) or manual inspection, reducing false rejects from surface contamination.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Adhesive Roller Cleaning Methods</h3>
      <p>
        Most DGSDK industrial cleaning machines use adhesive roller cleaning methods. Precision silicone or specialized adhesive rollers contact the substrate surface and lift particles by adhesion. This approach does not require compressed air, water treatment, or chemical waste management. The cleaning action is mechanical and consistent across every substrate that passes through the machine.
      </p>
      <p>
        Adhesive rollers transfer particles to a secondary paper roll or cleaning tape. Quick-change window structures allow roller and paper roll replacement in minutes. This minimizes line downtime and keeps cleaning performance stable long term, even in high-volume production environments.
      </p>

      <h3>Circuit Board Cleaning Machine vs. Manual Cleaning</h3>
      <p>
        Manual cleaning of circuit boards introduces inconsistency. Human contact with board surfaces adds contamination from skin oils, static discharge, and uneven cleaning pressure. Manual cleaning also slows production throughput and increases labor costs. An automated circuit board cleaning machine delivers consistent performance at line speed, without the quality variation that manual cleaning introduces. For production environments where yield and consistency matter, automated cleaning solutions replace manual cleaning at every critical process point.
      </p>

      <h3>Cleaning Machines for Tight Spaces and Compact Layouts</h3>
      <p>
        Factory floor space is often limited. Not every production line has room for a large inline cleaning system. DGSDK offers compact cleaning machine designs that fit into tight spaces between existing process equipment. The <a href="/products/cleaning-machine/pcb-vertical-cleaner">PCB Vertical Cleaning System</a> uses a vertical substrate path to minimize the horizontal footprint. This makes it practical to install a circuit board cleaning machine in tight spaces where conventional horizontal machines would not fit. Compact cleaning solutions reduce the barrier to adding automated cleaning at any point in the production line.
      </p>

      <h3>Choosing the Right Circuit Board Cleaning Machine</h3>
      <p>
        The correct circuit board cleaning machine depends on your substrate type, line configuration, throughput, and contamination profile. For SMT production lines, the <a href="/products/cleaning-machine/smt-cleaner">SMT600 Series inline cleaner</a> integrates directly into the conveyor flow. For small to medium line layouts where floor space is limited, the <a href="/products/cleaning-machine/pcb-vertical-cleaner">PCB Vertical Cleaning Machine</a> offers a compact footprint. For FPC and film substrates requiring high-precision handling, the multi-axis <a href="/products/cleaning-machine/fpc-4-axis-cleaner">FPC 4-Axis</a> and <a href="/products/cleaning-machine/fpc-8-axis-cleaner">FPC 8-Axis cleaning machines</a> provide the substrate control needed to avoid deformation. Contact us with your substrate dimensions, line speed, and contamination requirements for a configuration recommendation.
      </p>
